<br>
When we first started, I sent a tell asking the warrior if he wanted me to stun in incoming. I was basically offering a low risk method for him to piggyback aggro. He wasn't interested. We fought for a bit, and he was having occasional problems with aggro. It wasn't anything terrible, just a convenience thing more than anything, but it was more of a difference from my own aggro abilities than I thought was needed. <br>
<br>
He was pulling with a bow. When the mob got into camp him and I would engage for a few seconds before debuffs started getting cast. Generally half the mobs would aggro a debuffer during this initial engagement period, but the warrior usually got it back pretty quickly. Probably pretty standard for a warrior, i'm guessing.<br>
<br>
During one particular pull, my wife slowed the mob too early and got aggro. She sent a tell to the warrior saying basically &quot;Oops, sorry. I'm used to Graal tanking&quot; The warrior understandably got a bit miffed at that and responded &quot;I'm a good tank&quot;. My wife responded by saying that first, she was spoiled and it had nothing to with him, and that secondly, when I was tanking she HAD to slow immediately.<br>
<br>
Some time went by and I decided I was going to help the warrior by letting him piggyback aggro from me. I would stand right next to him when the mob was coming in and stun it as soon as it engaged the warrior. Usually the warrior had aggro by the time the stun wore off and things went much more smoothly. A few times he didn't get aggro very quickly from me and I almost died. It wasn't nearly as hard for him to tank the mobs unslowed as it was for me, but he had a level (2 by the end of the night) and better gear than me.<br>
<br>
After a while, when he pulled he set up right next to me so I didn't have to move next to him. Things worked really well and we clicked.<br>
<br>
If I had been the MT, aggro would not have been a problem unless people were really stupid and/or lazy. He definitely tanked better than I did, but not in relation to my aggro abilities. I think that the balance between aggro and tanking needs to be tweaked a little bit. My concern is that SOE uses a sledgehammer to tweak. If I as a paladin don't have an advantage in the taunting department, I don't have a role in a group. Keep in mind this is a person who has a ready made group waiting for him when he logs in. It's not something that would affect me, but it would really hurt most other paladins.<br>
<br>
I want to make sure that most warriors understand something. When a paladin is MT, he is basically devoting his manapool just to aggro and generally can't afford to use spells for anything else, at least not in a sustained manner. If I have to cast 3 stuns throughout a fight to keep a mob on me (which is about right), that is more mana used than my mana regen can make up for. My mana is slowly going down as I tank. Granted it will be a long time before the gas tank is empty if I use my mana wisely, but if I use any other spells such as a heal over time or a group heal, it is a big hit on my mana. If I have to use my mana for anything other than just aggro, I quickly have to sit and med. I just wanted to point that out so people undertood that a tanking paladin really doesn't bring that much extra utility to a group simply due to the requirements of using mana to aggro. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14686">Graal MacBladefury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
