<br>
First off, 28 pts of weapon skill is worth somewhere around 75+ Raw Attack.  There is absolutely no doubt in my mind, or anyone else who has parsed the differences between comparably equipped Paladins and Warriors, what this means for DPS.  Flat out, and respectfully as I can say this as possible, you do more damage, period.. lets not debate something that is clear and unequivocally true.  Whether you do *enough* more damage to balance against all the other things could be debated.  Remember, however, that Hybrids were specifically given better combat tables because of how incredibly pathetic they once were.<br>
<br>
As a Paladin, for the first time in about 2 years I enjoy what my class brings to a group.  I think I bring enough to justify myself in that tank position at least 50% of the time when a group is looking for a tank and an SK or a Warrior is also LFG.  I don't think it is an immediate decision to take a hybrid over a warrior, and I have asked my regular group cleric many times how things compare with an equivalently equipped warrior tanking for him, and he essentially tells me he the warrior tanks better, but that I hold aggro better.<br>
<br>
I think there is room for an improvement to the Warrior ability to hold taunt, but if the concept is not broached intelligently, there is a very real possibility of breaking things.  In uber mob raid content, there is no need for an increase to warrior taunt, and part of the problem is that most ideas put forth to fix it will also effect it in that arena.<br>
<br>
I am all for improvements to the Warrior class that allow them to be on par in an exp group situation to a Hybrid tank, if there really is a spreading idea that Warriors are inferior in this regard (I am not wholly convinced of it, but I'll consider it as a valid opinion).  When you compare available spells that can be used while tanking, the dps of the two parties (since DPS stacks, while tanking does not), and the margin of tanking that a Warrior holds over a Hybrid, only then can you balance the taunt factors.<br>
<br>
I generally believe there is a large deal of anxiety because of the limited areas and opportunities to exp in PoP exp groups... I think you will find most classes are not satisfied with their ability to find groups.  I also think, that as tanks, at least we can be assured of one group spot in a group, whereas alot of other classes compete under the broad category of &quot;DPS&quot; for their group spots.  DPS, conveniently for them however, stacks, while tanking, as we well know, does not.<br>
<br>
Unless they want to go adding Rampaging mobs to exp grind areas, there really is never a reason to have 2 tanks in a group, and I believe therein lies the real problem.  If you think for a second that a Paladin has some better chance of grabbing the '2nd tank' group position then any other tank class, your sadly mistaken.  In fact, when the tanking end is covered, a Warrior is above the Paladin on the list, simply because they add more DPS.<br>
<br>
In summary, I am for research into the area of Warrior taunt, and an increase to it that 'makes sense'.  I don't want to see a return to the days of Kunark, where thankfully, exp mobs were so easy in comparison to those of today, that the utterly horribly designed and balanced Hybrid classes got groups only out of charity.  If, as Warriors, you can concede that you will and should be vying for tanking positions in exp groups with Paladins and Shadowknights, I have no problem with class tweakings to your class that make that area more level.  If, however, the goal is to make the Warrior class the absolute best class to take for that 1 available exp group tanking position, it will absolutely swing the scale of class balance back to days of yore.<br>
<br>
There are more Warriors then Paladins and Shadowknights put together on nearly every server.  It is not by chance that this is the case, it stems from a very long period of time where the Hybrid classes flat out stunk.  They stunk for exp groups, they stunk in raids... there wasnt an area of the game or a knowledgeable exp group in the game that would take one over a Warrior.<br>
<br>
If both of our classes can understand that true balance will still mean us vying for the same exp group spots (tank position), and not a clearcut winner from either side in 95% of situations, then we can start to work together on an acceptable outcome.  For me, as a Paladin, this means I must consider the fact that my class, at this point in the games cycle, may be slightly overbalanced in comparison to Warriors in exp situations, due almost exclusively to my ability to taunt.  For you, as a Warrior, you must concede that for most of the previous history of the game from Kunark onward, you held this position of overbalance without equal or peer.<br>
<br>
Push for the changes to be made where they really matter, which is before a Warrior can attain a taunt-enducing weapon.  When a Warrior gains access to those weapons, I believe the classes are very nearly completely balanced. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 764<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/29/03 12:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2815.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: re</span><hr size=1> All of the nice theorizing aside, I know that some of my friends, particularly people who tend to draw aggro more than most, Druids, Wizards, Rogues, Monks, Shaman, have all told me that while a Warrior makes a good tank, they can participate more and unload more with a Knight tanking.  My Druid friends have come right out and told me there are entire lines of spells they don't feel comfortable using if a Warrior is tanking because of the aggro involved.<br>
